Introduction¶

Overview: In this data set we will be analyzing data collected for TMDB 10,000 movies, this data contains information about movies such as their title, release date, genre, runtime, original budget and the movie revenue. the purpose of this investigation is to find out independant factors that affect movies final revenue and how, factors that will be looked at are such as original budget for the movie, movie run time and genre.

#this function generates scatter plots by taking arguments 
def scatter_plot(x,y,graph_title,x_label,y_label):
    """the function takes the x-axis, Y-axis,title (as a string) ,x-label (as string) & Y-label(as string) as arguments and generate a scatter plot"""
    plt.scatter(x,y)
    plt.title(graph_title)
    plt.xlabel(x_label)
    plt.ylabel(y_label)
    plt.show()

this shows that we have some outlier runtimes that need to be removed first to be able to asses the relation between runtime and revenue first we need to address thyem IQR = 21 outliers would be 1.5 * IQR above and lower Q1 & Q3 so we will exclude values higher than 142 minutes and lower than 58 minutes

In [21]:
runtime_without_outliers = df[(df['runtime'] > 58) & (df['runtime'] < 142)]
scatter_plot(runtime_without_outliers['runtime'],runtime_without_outliers['revenue'],"relation between runtime of a movie and its revenue","runtime","revenue")

as a conclusion from our scatter plot we can see that the movie revenue isn't affected by movie runtime unless movie runtime is below 85 minutes, all movies below 85 minutes didn't acheive as high revenue as movies with higher runtime

    print('the mean revenue of ' + str(i) +' '+ str(int(mean_revenue)) + ' USD')
    mean_rev_list.append(mean_revenue)

Conclusions¶

I received the data for about 10,000 TMDB movies, the original data had some irrelevant topics for my investigation such as but not limited to movie homepage and an overview of the movie. first problem I encountered was some budget values being equal to zero which will corrupt the analysis, So I had to drop them. Genres column was alittle messy so I had to separate every genre in one separate column. after finishing my investigation, the results is as follows :

  1. The revenue of a movie doesn't depend on movie run time unless the movie is too short and by too short I mean less than 80 minutes long
  2. Spending more money on movie production most of the times lead to higher revenue.
  3. Some movie genres have higher revenue than others such as animation and fantasy, So including these genres in a movie will certainly have a positive effect on its revenue

for item number 2, it could be useful to have further data on the spent budget to be able to analyze the more effecient ways of distributing the budget like how much was spent on cast salaries, and director salary and other spending directions, if these data was available we could have known which part of the spent budget contributed in increasing the revenue of the movie.
